<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
>>Asterix, I'd LOVE to know where you got this information from. Frankly, unless you have a source who's got access to Verant's code I'd have to say this is just another example of someone taking a wild guess and stating it as truth.<P>No, it's not a wild guess.  It's a commonly accepted theory by enchanters that have bothered to test it.  Obviously, without Verant confirming it, we can't be 100% sure, but since it matches perfectly, we run with it.<P>>>You can test this by using ToT at the start of a fight and seeing how much mana is returned. <P>Actually, you can't.  ToTs mana returned has nothing to do with how much mana the mob has.  Zero, nada, nilch.  ToT does return less mana on some mobs than others.  It seems to be level based but we've never bothered to track it down exactly.  Easy enough to verify in game if you want.  Go ToT any mana using mob under 50 and see how much mana you get.  You will get the full amount on every single one.  But you can drain most of the low level ones with a single seive.  Takes more than that to drain your HoT mob.  Also, you're wrong about the mana pool, mob mana pool is generally based on level (but not always).  Seb Mycanoids take about 2-3 seives to drain.  HoT mobs in ToV take 3-4.<P>Now, as to the common knowledge bit...<P>Take one of your HoT worms.  You aren't trying to kill it here, so don't kill it super fast.  Seive it dry.  4 seives.  Don't cast seive again but now start beating the crud out of it (just not too fast).  Observe that it tries to gate.  Now, post CR, snag the worm again.  This time, seive all you want, like normal, but no Torment.  This is when you'll get the Mob attempts to Gate message without the begins to cast message.  This happens when a mob has mana, but not enough to actually cast gate.  Now pull another worm and slap Torment of Argli on it + seive it dry.  It won't attempt to gate at all.<P>If you want to have more fun, go to Seb, drain a mycanoid adept dry.  Observe how often it casts.  Kill it, pull another.  Seive it dry as well.  Now cast Wandering Mind on it.  Wandering Mind is bugged, it works in reverse.  It lowers your mana regen and raises the targets.  Observe the adept chain cast greater healing.  Wandering Mind raises mana regen by 6 per tick.  That 6 per tick let the mob chain cast to it's heart's content.  But it wasn't enough to let it cast CH, which it would do if it had enough mana.<P>So what we have there is the following: a 60th level mob has a considerably smaller mana pool than a 60th level player (at least one with gear).  You certainly won't drain me dry in 3-4 casts.  Next, an untormented mob will cast again, after a while.  It will also give the attempts to gate message.  A tormented one won't even try.  A step further, a mob that was dry will chain cast a 150 mana spell when all we do is raise it's mana regen by 6 per tick.<P>Now, on the basis of all this, I (and most others) conclude that:<BR>A: mobs have small mana pools.<BR>B: mob mana regen is low.<BR>C: Mobs pay a discounted price for spells.<P>If you've got a different theory to explain it all, I'd love to hear it.  But for now, until a situation arises that proves this theory wrong or someone comes up with a better theory, it's the one pretty much all informed enchanters run with.<P>Oh, and just for the record, Verant has stated in response to a question about dispelling a mob so that it would rebuff itself repeatedly, back when dispels didn't cause aggro, that you couldn't drain a mob of its mana this way because mobs pay a severely discounted price to buff.  Verant didn't say that mobs pay a discounted price for all spells... but they didn't say mobs didn't either  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0">
</FONT>
