<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>ToT has nothing at all to do with mana pool. Try hunting in Guk, keep a wiz mob mezzed- you can ToT in nonstop when it pops<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>Of course you can, the mob is mezzed (=not casting spells) and regenning enough mana between casts of ToT to keep the return constant...  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>torment a caster mob and keep it rooted. Then test ToT on it several times; you might get a bit less if the resist roll goes high enough<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>Resist?? Sorry, but do you know how ToT works? If you argli a mob and cast several ToTs on it, you will get less mana on the latter ToTs because the mob has less mana to drain, resists have nothing to do with it.<BR> <BR>Asterix, if you haven't seen differences in the amount of mana returned by ToT on the same type of mob, then you just haven't been looking. I noticed this way back at level 51 when I started using it. I'm surprised this isn't common knowledge as it's so obvious.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Repeat mez/fear/dd until 2 minute mark but dont kill it.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>Don't know about you, but I will regen a lot of mana in 2 mins even standing up the whole time. Mobs have a limited spell-book, if they're 1 less mana than the amount needed to cast CH they'll often cast a much lower spell simply because they don't have better spells available. <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>If blurred and let sit for a few seconds it would regen mana VERY quickly and CH itself<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>Haha, have you ever tried blurring a dragon mid-fight? It puts it into a reset cycle and effectively gives it a free CH, I wouldn't be surprised if the same applies to resetting the mana pool. Sorry, but this doesn't apply to mana-regen on aggroed mobs.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>ToT is based on level of the mob in comparison to the caster<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>WRONG, state the basis for your opinion. My mana pool at level 60 is bigger than it was when I was level 51. Not surprisingly, I see less return from ToT now on seb frogs than I did from the same frogs when I was 51.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>One of the developers confirmed that monsters regen mana MUCH more slowly during combat, than they do out of combat.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>Exactly, that corresponds with my experience on charmed caster mobs. It seems that mobs get a similar meditation bonus out of combat that players get when sitting down. Different mobs seem to have different non-combat reset cycles though. Some will effectively CH as soon as non-aggro, whereas others will regen much slower when non-aggro.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>That means I'm sieving out aprox 1200 mana from an adept just to try and prevent it from CHing.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>Which would mean that myconid adepts (I assume that's what you're talking about) have a mana pool of less than 1600. This would be very low for a level 56 player, though it fits in with the scheme of higher-level mobs having smaller mana pools.
</FONT>
